From the locals, the house soon after its completion earned the nickname "House of Bones" thanks to its organic shapes.
Others called it a "singing house" because of the specific mechanism of opening the windows.
It is also said that on the top of the building is likened to the sword of St. George, patron of Catalonia.
Hidden religious motifs also contain other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> designed the house for his time a unique central heating system with vents and typical chimneys.
Bizarre may seem their forty-five-degree inclination.
In Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s creation, he absolutely did not respect the construction regulations of the time and did not allow himself to be bound by them.
At the beginning of the construction, he obtained a building permit from the city, but the data on the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later, when it was completed, the city council was devastated and requested a correction.
