Microbes with arsenic resistance increase the possibility of new types of life on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, expands the space to search for new life forms on Earth and perhaps even further.
Researchers have discovered an unusual bacterium here on Earth and claim it is a sign that life has possibilities that stand out from the main elements that have so far been considered and fundamental.
"This organism has a double ability."
"It can grow by either phosphorus or arsenic."
“This fact is very strange, but it’s not proof that it’s some form of truly ‘foreign’ life,” commented Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of a report that appeared Thursday in the online journal Science.
For a long time, it was considered necessary for life six main elements - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, scientists have found that bacteria discovered in Mono Lake, California, are able to continue to grow after phosphorus is replaced by arsenic.
"You'll start to wonder what's still possible," said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report.
This finding is important for the search for life beyond Earth because researchers need to be able to recognize life and know what life can look like, Anbar said.
The study focuses on microbes found on Earth.
However, a report on this novelty published to discuss it, which did not reveal the details of the finding, has sparked widespread speculation on the Internet that the report reveals the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
It's not like that.
The discovery "shows that other planetary organisms may be able to use other elements that drive biochemistry, and that a set of elements that we consider 'standard' may not be so absolutely necessary for life," explained Charles Cockell, Professor of Planetary and Space Sciences at the Miltons University, Open Research Institute.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is unusual because it shows the replacement of one element by another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
It wasn't a coincidence.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon from NASA’s Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it exhibits high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, so consider that a microbe that is exposed to both elements may be able to replace one after the other.
"Arsenic is poisonous mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus."
"The result is that organisms can very hardly separate these elements from each other."
"However, arsenic is so different that it doesn't work like phosphorus. When it gets into the body, it starts working in biochemical processes," Anbar explained.
Scientists collect bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and expose them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which bacteria are able to adapt and grow.
Microbes grow better with phosphorus, but since they can also survive with arsenic replacement, the chances are that a life form that uses arsenic can occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea of arsenic, which could be replaced with phosphorus, is not new, but there has never been an example of this.
Arsenic was more common in earlier times on Earth, she said, and so scientists speculated that earlier forms of life could have used it.
"This suggests that there could be other ways to create life, not just the way it was created in the early Earth," said Foster, who was not part of the Wolfe-Simon research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
