Provoking a yellow card under similar conditions is not a new practice, but is more or less common in football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos of football, i.e. rules that are not written, but are followed.
Part of the discussion in this case was due to the fact that its participant was the team of Real Madrid (who in his anthem boasts nobility and honor, and who already penalized for similar acts of his players), and, as it seems, also thanks to the epitome of the next.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of conduct, which is not expressly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether there is circumvention of the law in these acts; it is indeed an action that respects the rules of sport, the meaning of which is, however,
It is decided what kind of harm such behavior affects the sporting spirit.
One of the duties of sporting behavior is the physical inviolability of the opponents, which has not been violated in these cases, i.e. there has been no violent play.
Another of these duties that characterize a clean game is to avoid players having an advantage over the opponent's team due to their offense - which has not happened here either.
So the paradox of the action of Real Madrid players is the fact that what we normally characterize as a leash or circumvention of the law did not occur, there was no covert violation of the rules in order to avoid sanctions, but this behavior should be as visible as possible with the aim of punishment.
They waited and liked to be punished.
The other question, however, is what benefit the perpetrators of their deliberate offense will have.
Here it is necessary to note that the opponent does not get into the disadvantaged position, and that in the current match no benefit is achieved, since the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
Nor is it a useful strategy for the next match, as the club will not be able to count on these players.
The advantage obviously lies in the fact that players begin the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could jeopardize their participation in the future match.
However, this is an advantage from a long-term perspective and with a certain degree of uncertainty, so at first glance the team can be eliminated, and beyond this, the players will be punished, and they will go to the second round of cards, in which the first round is not enough to rule out one of my cards.
So as the wheels will continue, it will not be entirely clear whether this is an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the sporting spirit, the part of which is to make a strategic decision that will allow you to get the maximum benefit under the rules.
in the case that we are dealing with here, the players were not intended to avoid the award of a penalty (which would be a clear case of circumvention of the rules), but rather they chose when to submit to it.
They made strategic decisions without evading the punishment or running away from it.
Although the boundary between a joke and circumventing the rules is not quite clear, I believe that in this case it was clearly a joke.
It seems to me that the controversy arises for two reasons: because it was two self-exclusions and because of the way in which the transmission of instructions to provoke them from the leadership took place.
Damage to sporting principles by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
