The United States is changing the rules for the issuance of visas
People will have to contact the Visa Applicant Service centres before an interview with the Consular Department; the costs will be lower and the waiting time will be shortened.
As of January 10, 2011, the process of negotiating visas at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to contact the Visa Applicant Services (abbreviated from ASC) centres before an interview with the Consular Department.
The ASC staff will collect the biometric information of the applicant and will be evaluated by the Consular Department before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including the following:
The total cost of handling the visa will be lower, there will no longer be a fee to arrange a meeting, the second to process the request and the other to deliver the document by a transport service.
The applicant will only pay a single fee covering all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: the amount corresponding to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa applications (including temporary workers visas) and $390 for a visa for traders and investors.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to interview a consular officer, but will only contact the nearest ASC, where they will submit their documents and will be stripped of their fingerprints.
Since biometric information will be collected at the ASC, applicants who will require a second meeting with the interview at the Consular Department will spend a shorter time here than in the past.
Similarly, those who apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra $26 service fee.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
