Climate: How France hacked its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to try to keep the promises of fast-start financing (fast-start or early-start financing) implemented by developed countries.
And the big French hacks have been revealed
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion for three years and France pledged <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.26 billion (420 million a year).
At the launch of COP16, the EU has drawn a big ace to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start funding: a report detailing the actions of its Member States, a press conference, a grand side event, the distribution of brochures...
Transparent operations are invaluable and valued at their true value: advanced countries and civil society would like all advanced countries and civil society to do them the same and with the same degree of accuracy.
The EU announces that it has released <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, leading it on the right track to deliver on its <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion pledge in 2012.
But if we focus on the detail, we will find that things are much more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, these funds are "new and additional" to ensure that the increased burden is realised without detriment to the public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus in what is meant by "new and additional".
While the European Commission has proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that best suits them.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 as a reference: international funding has remained and it adds 150 million to the three-year fast start funding title.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment dates or with dates at the level of public development assistance.
France, on the other hand, considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or to the global level of Public Aid for Development d'Aide publique au développement.
In particular, the total amount of aid granted by France to developing countries may remain unchanged (or even decrease) and must comply with its commitment to finance "new and additional" projects.
Another crucial element is the division into gifts and loans.
There is no rule there yet and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as France, believe that 1<0xE2><0x82><0xAC> borrowed is equal to 1<0xE2><0x82><0xAC> donated.
Obviously, this is hard to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be documented for some investments that are profitable (often they are projects related to emission reductions, based on more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro coin, which we get as a p-value, as a p-value, a p-value, a p-value, a-value, a-value, a-value, a-value, a-value, a-value, a-value, a-value, a-value, a-value, a-value-value--value-value------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
But France can only give such a justification: it "remains" its 420 million euro commitment, of which 91.5% makes a loan (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to verify it for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that makes use of the loan on such a scale.
Germany has requested 46% from this, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) are complying with their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union gives <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 to fulfill their promise, France gives only 10 cents and considers this effort comparable.
A beautiful cheetah piece!
To sum up, in its "fast start" financing, France operates with a double sheikh: on the one hand, with the development of stocks in time, and on the other, with a real financial burden.
Despite spending only <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million, he is able to convince that he is spending <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million "new and additional" in connection with his promises.
The manipulation of the Minister of Finance (because it seems that although it is Bercy who made such a decision) could have a double negative impact, at the same time within the EU (why should Member States continue to donate if it is enough to borrow?) and in the negotiations, because development is not progressing?
The chapter on early funding is only a small, relatively short-term issue in relation to a series of climate debates.
But it could also be a grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope this isn't our case.
Whatever it is, it is necessary to draw on the knowledge of this first year of early funding.
First, France should announce a change in its way of keeping accounts for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of compliance with its obligations and fairness and fairness towards the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid discussions about investments in long-term financing (another key chapter currently being discussed): we will not avoid the question of "additionality" or the way in which loans are accounted for.
France should change its stance to become as progressive with these deposits as with the rest.
